# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: evolution
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The **1860 Oxford evolution debate** took place at the Oxford University Museum in Oxford, England, on 7 July 1860, seven months after the publication of Charles Darwin's *On the Origin of Species*.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Several prominent British scientists and philosophers participated, including Thomas Henry Huxley, Bishop Samuel Wilberforce, Benjamin Brodie, Joseph Dalton Hooker and Robert FitzRoy.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The encounter is often known as the **Huxley–Wilberforce debate** or the **Wilberforce–Huxley debate**, although this description is somewhat misleading.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Although Huxley and Wilberforce were not the only participants in the discussion, they were reported to be the two dominant parties.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The debate is best remembered today for a heated exchange in which Wilberforce supposedly asked Huxley whether it was through his grandfather or his grandmother that he claimed his descent from a monkey.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Huxley is said to have replied that he would not be ashamed to have a monkey for his ancestor, but he would be ashamed to be connected with a man who used his great gifts to obscure the truth.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] However, what Huxley and Wilberforce actually said is uncertain, and subsequent accounts were subject to distortion since no verbatim account of the debate exists.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The idea of transmutation of species was seen as contrary to religious orthodoxy and a threat to the social order and thus was very controversial in the first half of the nineteenth century, although Radicals seeking to widen democracy and overturn the aristocratic hierarchy welcomed it.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The scientific community was wary in the absence of a proposed mechanism.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The anonymous publication of *Vestiges of the Natural History of Creation*, supporting the idea of transmutation of species, in 1844 brought a storm of controversy but attracted wide readership and became a bestseller.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] At the British Association for the Advancement of Science meeting at Oxford in May 1847, the Bishop of Oxford Samuel Wilberforce used his Sunday sermon at St.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Mary's Church on "the wrong way of doing science" to deliver a stinging attack obviously aimed at its author, Robert Chambers, in a church "crowded to suffocation" with archaeologists, geoscientists, astronomers, chemists, physicists, and biologists.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The scientific establishment also remained skeptical, but the book had convinced a vast popular audience.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Charles Darwin's *On the Origin of Species* was published on 24 November 1859 to wide debate and controversy.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Influential biologist Richard Owen wrote an anonymous negative review of the book in the *Edinburgh Review* and coached Wilberforce, who also wrote an anonymous 17,000-word review in the *Quarterly Review*.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Thomas Henry Huxley, one of the small group with whom Darwin had shared his theory before publication, emerged as the main public champion of evolution.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] He wrote a favourable review of "*Origin*" in *The Times* in December 1859, along with several other articles, and delivered a lecture at the Royal Institution in February 1860.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The reaction of many orthodox churchmen was hostile, but their attention was diverted in February 1860 by a much greater furore over the publication of *Essays and Reviews* by seven liberal theologians.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Amongst them, the Reverend Baden Powell had already praised evolutionary ideas, and in his essay he commended "Mr.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Darwin's masterly volume" for substantiating "the grand principle of the self-evolving powers of nature".
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The controversy was at the centre of attention when the British Association for the Advancement of Science (often referred to then simply as "the BA") convened their annual meeting at the new Oxford University Museum of Natural History in June 1860.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] On Thursday 28 June, Charles Daubeny read a paper "On the final causes of the sexuality in plants, with particular reference to Mr.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Darwin's work..." Owen and Huxley were both in attendance, and a debate erupted over Darwin's theory.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Owen spoke of facts which would enable the public to "come to some conclusions ... of the truth of Mr.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] For the first time he spoke publicly on this point and "denied altogether that the difference between the brain of the gorilla and man was so great" in a "direct and unqualified contradiction" of Owen, citing previous studies as well as promising to provide detailed support for his position.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Wilberforce agreed to address the meeting on Saturday morning, and there was expectation that he would repeat his success at scourging evolutionary ideas as at the 1847 meeting.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Huxley was initially reluctant to engage Wilberforce in a public debate about evolution, but, in a chance encounter, Robert Chambers persuaded him not to desert the cause.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The Reverend Baden Powell would have been on the platform, too, but he had died of a heart attack on 11 June.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Word spread that Bishop Samuel Wilberforce would speak against Darwin's theory at the meeting on Saturday 30 June 1860.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Wilberforce was one of the greatest public speakers of his day but was known as "Soapy Sam" (from a comment by Benjamin Disraeli that the Bishop's manner was "unctuous, oleaginous, saponaceous").
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] According to Bryson, "more than a thousand people crowded into the chamber; hundreds more were turned away." Darwin himself was too sick to attend.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The discussion was chaired by John Stevens Henslow, Darwin's former mentor from Cambridge.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] It has been suggested that Owen arranged for Henslow to chair the discussion "hoping to make the expected defeat of Darwin the more complete".
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The main focus of the meeting was supposed to be a lecture by New York University's John William Draper, "On the Intellectual Development of Europe, considered with reference to the views of Mr.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Darwin and others, that the progression of organisms is determined by law".
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] By all accounts, Draper's presentation was long and boring.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] After Draper had finished, Henslow called on several other speakers, including Benjamin Brodie, the president of the Royal Society, before it was Wilberforce's turn.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] According to Lucas, "Wilberforce, contrary to the central tenet of the legend, did not prejudge the issue", but Lucas is in a minority on this, as Jensen makes clear.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Wilberforce criticised Darwin's theory on ostensibly scientific grounds, arguing that it was not supported by the facts, and he noted that the greatest names in science were opposed to the theory.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] According to a letter written 30 years later to Francis Darwin, when Huxley heard this he whispered to Brodie, "The Lord hath delivered him into mine hands".
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Huxley's own contemporary account, in a letter to Henry Dyster on September 9, 1860, makes no mention of this remark.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Huxley rose to defend Darwin's theory, finishing his speech with the now-legendary assertion that he was not ashamed to have a monkey for his ancestor, but he would be ashamed to be connected with a man who used great gifts to obscure the truth.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Later retellings indicate that this statement had a tremendous effect on the audience, and Lady Brewster is said to have fainted.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Reliable accounts indicate that although Huxley did respond with the "monkey" retort, the remainder of his speech was unremarkable.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Next, Henslow called upon Admiral Robert FitzRoy, who had been Darwin's captain and companion on the voyage of the *Beagle* twenty-five years earlier.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] FitzRoy denounced Darwin's book and, "lifting an immense Bible first with both hands and afterwards with one hand over his head, solemnly implored the audience to believe God rather than man".
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] According to his own account, it was he and not Huxley who delivered the most effective reply to Wilberforce's arguments: "Sam was shut up—had not one word to say in reply, and the meeting was dissolved forthwith".
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Ruse claims that "everybody enjoyed himself immensely and all went cheerfully off to dinner together afterwards".
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] It is said that during the debate, two Cambridge dons happened to be standing near Wilberforce, one of whom was Henry Fawcett, the recently blinded economist.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Fawcett was asked whether he thought the bishop had actually read the *Origin of Species*.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] "Oh no, I would swear he has never read a word of it", Fawcett reportedly replied loudly.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Wilberforce swung round to him scowling, ready to recriminate, but stepped back and bit his tongue on noting that the protagonist was the blind economist.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Notably, all three major participants felt they had had the best of the debate.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Wilberforce wrote that, "On Saturday Professor Henslow ... called on me by name to address the Section on Darwin's theory.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] So I could not escape and had quite a long fight with Huxley.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Summary reports of the debate were published in *The Manchester Guardian*, *The Athenaeum* and *Jackson's Oxford Journal*.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] A more detailed report was published by the *Oxford Chronicle*.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Both sides immediately claimed victory, but the majority opinion has always been that the debate represented a major victory for the Darwinians.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] Though the debate is frequently depicted as a clash between religion and science, the British Association at the time had a number of clergymen occupying high positions (including Presidents of two of its seven sections).
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] On the other hand, Oxford academic Dr Diane Purkiss says the debate "was really the first time Christianity had ever been asked to square off against science in a public forum in the whole of its history".
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The debate has been called "one of the great stories of the history of science" and it is often regarded as a key moment in the acceptance of evolution.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] However, at the time it received only a few passing references in newspapers, and Brooke argues that "the event almost completely disappeared from public awareness until it was resurrected in the 1890s as an appropriate tribute to a recently deceased hero of scientific education".
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The debate began a bitter three-year dispute between Owen and Huxley over human origins, satirised by Charles Kingsley as the "Great Hippocampus Question", which concluded with the defeat of Owen and his backers.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] The play *Darwin in Malibu* by Crispin Whittell, was inspired by the debate.
[src:evolution/1860-oxford-evolution-debate] A commemorative pillar marks the 150th anniversary of the debate.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] Kaiser received in 1950 his bachelor's degree from Purdue University and in 1955 his PhD from Caltech in biology.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] At Caltech he was in Max Delbrück's bacteriophage group and received his PhD in biology under Jean Weigle with thesis *A genetic analysis of bacteriophage lambda*.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] Kaiser was in 1956 a postdoc at the Pasteur Institute in Paris (where he worked in Francois Jacob's group) and afterward became an instructor and then in 1958 an assistant professor in microbiology at Washington University in St.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] In 1959 he became an assistant professor at Stanford University, where in 1966 he became a professor for biochemistry at Stanford University School of Medicine.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] From 1989-2020 he was also a professor of developmental biology.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] In the beginning of his career, Kaiser concentrated on the molecular genetics of bacteriophage lambda.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] He was especially concerned with the control mechanisms for lysogeny.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] He found one of the first examples of self-regulation of a gene (*cI*, the repressor gene of lambda phage) and later did pioneering work on molecular chaperones.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] Some of the methods developed by Kaiser's laboratory became important in genetic engineering.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] In the 1970s he worked on the developmental biology of swarms of myxobacteria.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] In the 2000s his laboratory team did research on genetic and biochemical methods to control the swarm and propagation behavior of the bacterial species *Myxococcus xanthus*.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] When starved, the *Myxococcus* bacteria aggregate together to make fruiting bodies, each with approximately $10^{5}$ spores; the form of the fruiting body is species-specific.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] Kaiser's laboratory succeeded in the identification and molecular elucidation of the roles of a series of molecular messengers in the swarm and propagation behavior of *Myxococcus*.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] Steel Foundation Award in Molecular Biology, in 1980 the Albert Lasker Award for Basic Medical Research, in 1981 the Waterford Biomedical Science Award, in 1997 the Abbott Lifetime Achievement Award of the American Society for Microbiology and in 1991 the Thomas Hunt Morgan Medal.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] In 1970 he was elected a member of the National Academy of Sciences and a member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] In 1993 Kaiser was the president of the Genetics Society of America.
[src:evolution/a-dale-kaiser] Born in Piqua, Ohio, Kaiser died in Stanford, California.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:evolution/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] In ecology, **abiotic components** or **abiotic factors** are non-living chemical and physical parts of the environment that affect living organisms and the functioning of ecosystems.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors and the phenomena associated with them underpin biology as a whole.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] They affect a wide range of species, across all forms of environmental conditions, such as marine or terrestrial animals.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] Humans can make or change abiotic factors in a species' environment.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] For instance, fertilizers can affect a snail's habitat, or the greenhouse gases which humans utilize can change marine pH levels.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] Abiotic components include physical conditions and non-living resources that affect living organisms in terms of growth, maintenance, and reproduction.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] Resources are distinguished as substances or objects in the environment required by one organism and consumed or otherwise made unavailable for use by other organisms.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] Component degradation of a substance occurs by chemical or physical processes, e.g. hydrolysis.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] All non-living components of an ecosystem, such as atmospheric conditions and water resources, are called abiotic components.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] In biology, abiotic factors can include water, light, radiation, temperature, humidity, atmosphere, acidity, salinity, precipitation, altitude, minerals, tides, rain, dissolved oxygen nutrients, and soil.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] The macroscopic climate often influences each of the above.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] Pressure and sound waves may also be considered in the context of marine or sub-terrestrial environments.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors in ocean environments also include aerial exposure, substrate, water clarity, solar energy and tides.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] Consider the differences in the mechanics of C3, C4, and CAM plants in regulating the influx of carbon dioxide to the Calvin-Benson Cycle in relation to their abiotic stressors.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] C3 plants have no mechanisms to manage photorespiration, whereas C4 and CAM plants utilize a separate PEP carboxylase enzyme to prevent photorespiration, thus increasing the yield of photosynthesis processes in certain high energy environments.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] Many Archea require very high temperatures, pressures, or unusual concentrations of chemical substances such as sulfur; this is due to their specialization into extreme conditions.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] In addition, fungi have also evolved to survive at the temperature, the humidity, and stability of their environment.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] For example, there is a significant difference in access to both water and humidity between temperate rain forests and deserts.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] This difference in water availability causes a diversity in the organisms that survive in these areas.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] These differences in abiotic components alter the species present by creating boundaries of what species can survive within the environment and influencing competition between two species.
[src:evolution/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors such as salinity can give one species a competitive advantage over another, creating pressures that lead to speciation and alteration of a species to and from generalist and specialist competitors.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Although biological evolution has been vocally opposed by some religious groups, many other groups accept the scientific position, sometimes with additions to allow for theological considerations.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The positions of such groups are described by terms including "theistic evolution", "theistic evolutionism" or "evolutionary creation".
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Of all the religious groups included on the chart, Buddhists are the most accepting of evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Theistic evolutionists believe that there is a God, that God is the creator of the material universe and (by consequence) all life within, and that biological evolution is a natural process within that creation.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Evolution, according to this view, is simply a tool that God employed to develop human life.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] According to Eugenie Scott, Director of the US National Center for Science Education, "In one form or another, Theistic Evolutionism is the view of creation taught at the majority of mainline Protestant seminaries, and it is the official position of the Catholic church".
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Theistic evolution is not a scientific theory, but a particular view about how the science of evolution relates to religious belief and interpretation.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Christian proponents of this view are sometimes described as Christian Darwinists.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Various biblical literalists have accepted or noted openness to this stance, including theologian B.B.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] A 2007 poll showed that acceptance among American Buddhists, Hindus and Jews was higher than among any Christian groups (graph below).
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] One recent survey, conducted by physicist Max Tegmark, on "of how different US faith communities view origins science, particularly evolution and Big Bang cosmology".
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] With this approach toward evolution, scriptural creation stories are typically interpreted as being allegorical in nature.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Both Jews and Christians had considered the idea of the Genesis creation history as an allegory (rather than as an historical description) long before the development of Darwin's theory.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] An example in Christianity would be the earlier writings by Saint Augustine (4th century), though he later rejected allegory in favor of literal interpretation.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] By this Augustine meant that in Genesis 1 the terms "light", "day", and "morning" hold a spiritual, rather than physical, meaning, and that this spiritual morning is just as literal as physical morning.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Theistic evolutionists may believe that creation is not literally a week-long process but a process beginning in the time of Genesis and continuing through all of time, including today.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] This view affirms that God created the world and was the primary causation of our being, while scientific changes such as evolution are part of "creatio continua" or continuing creation which is still occurring in the never ending process of creation.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] This is one possible way of interpreting biblical scriptures, such as Genesis, that seem otherwise to be in opposition to scientific theories, such as evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Many religious organizations accept evolutionary theory, though their related theological interpretations vary.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Additionally, individuals or movements within such organizations may not accept evolution, and stances on evolution may have adapted (or evolved) throughout history.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Buddhism is generally accepting of modern scientific theories about evolution, and more broadly the formation of the universe.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] This can be argued either from the standpoint that it simply does not matter, or from an interpretation of the Agañña Sutta favoring the notion that it describes the basic concept of evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] In the Aggañña Sutta, the 27th Sutta of the Digha Nikaya collection that can be found in the Pali Canon, the Buddha gives a highly detailed answer to this question of evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The idea of evolution is consonant with the teachings of the Buddha and is quite acceptable to the Buddhist; the findings of science fit in and do not contradict the fundamentals of his religion.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] No major principles of Buddhism contradict it, many Buddhists tacitly accept the theory of evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Questions about the eternity or infinity of the universe at large are counted among the 14 unanswered questions which the Buddha maintained were counterproductive areas of speculation.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] As such, many Buddhists do not think about these kinds of questions as meaningful for the Buddhist goal of relieving oneself and others from suffering.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Albert Low, a Zen master and author of *The Origin of Human Nature: A Zen Buddhist Looks at Evolution*, (2008) opposes neo-Darwinism and the selfish gene theory as he claims they are materialistic.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] He also opposes creationism for being dogmatic and instead advocates spiritual evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The Buddhist writer Anagarika Dharmapala even once stated that "the theory of evolution was one of the ancient teachings of the Buddha." However, it has long been taught that indifference to certain matters regarding life and its origins should be practised.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Asma has noted that the Buddha himself largely avoided answering questions about the origins of the universe.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Evolution contradicts a literalistic interpretation of Genesis; however, according to Catholicism and most contemporary Protestant denominations, biblical literalism in the creation account is not mandatory.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Christians have considered allegorical interpretations of Genesis since long before the development of Darwin's theory of evolution, or Hutton's principle of uniformitarianism.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Augustine (4th century), who, in his book, *De Genesi ad litteram* (*On the Literal Meaning of Genesis*), argued that everything in the universe was created by God in the same instant, and not in six days as a plain reading of Genesis would require.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] In this work, Augustine argues that "know [the days of creation] are different from the ordinary day of which we are familiar".
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] All of the traditional mainline Protestant denominations support or accept theistic evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The positions of particular denominations are discussed below.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] In a March 2006 interview, the then Archbishop of Canterbury Dr Rowan Williams expressed his thought that "creationism is, in a sense, a kind of category mistake, as if the Bible were a theory like other theories.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Whatever the biblical account of creation is, it's not a theory alongside theories...
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] My worry is creationism can end up reducing the doctrine of creation rather than enhancing it." His view is that creationism should not be taught in schools.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The United Methodist Church affirms a Creator God and supports the scientific study of evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Colling, author of *Random Designer* and professor at Olivet Nazarene University, received criticism from elements within the denomination in 2007 for his book (published in 2004), Darrel R.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Theologians of note in the denomination whose work on science and religion shows the promise of cooperation include Thomas Jay Oord (*Science of Love*, *The Altruism Reader*, *Defining Love*), Michael Lodahl (*God of Nature and of Grace*), and Samuel M.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] These theologians see no major problem reconciling theology with the general theory of evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The Nazarene *Manual*, a document crafted to provide Biblical guidance and denominational expression for Church members, states: "The Church of the Nazarene believes in the biblical account of creation ("In the beginning God created the heavens and the earth . . ."—Genesis 1:1).
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] We oppose any godless interpretation of the origin of the universe and of humankind.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] However, the church accepts as valid all scientifically verifiable discoveries in geology and other natural phenomena, for we firmly believe that God is the Creator.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The Eastern Orthodox Church includes two large categories which might be labeled as compatibilism and dualism.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] On the one hand, compatibilists hold that evolutionary science and theology are compatible and view them as complementary revelations of God.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Nicozisin (Father George) is a compatibilist.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] On the other hand, dualists hold that evolution can be incompatible with faith.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] They usually argue either that evolutionary science is philosophically based on a kind of naturalism or that God's specific revelation is infallible and therefore trumps the findings of human reason in the case of any conflict between faith and science.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] This is often based on a suspicion of human reason to arrive at reliable conclusions in the first place.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Their stance is somewhat similar to Averroism, in that there is one truth, but it can be arrived at through (at least) two different paths, namely philosophy and religion.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] V, is a dualist, preferring to see the spiritual level above the mechanical, physico-chemical, or biological levels; he attributes discrepancies between spiritual matters and scientific matters to be because of the purely naturalistic views of evolutionists.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The Church does not argue with scientists on matters such as the age of the Earth and the authenticity of the fossil record, seeing such matters as outside its area of expertise.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Papal pronouncements, along with commentaries by cardinals, indicate that the Church is aware of the general findings of scientists on the gradual appearance of life.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Indeed, Belgian priest Georges Lemaître, astronomer and physics professor at the Catholic University of Louvain, was the first to propose the theory of expansion of the universe, often incorrectly credited to Edwin Hubble.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] In the 1950 encyclical *Humani generis*, Pope Pius XII confirmed that there is no intrinsic conflict between Christianity and the theory of evolution, provided that Christians believe that the individual soul is a direct creation by God and not the product of purely material forces.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Today, many members of the Church support theistic evolution, also known as *evolutionary creation*.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Under Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, the International Theological Commission published a paper accepting the big bang of 15 billion years ago and the evolution of all life including humans from the microorganisms that formed approximately 4 billion years ago.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The Vatican has no official teaching on this matter except for the special creation of the human soul.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The Pontifical Biblical Commission issued a decree ratified by Pope Pius X on June 30, 1909, stating that special creation applies to humans and not other species.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Deism is belief in a God or first cause based on reason, rather than on faith or revelation.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Most deists believe that God does not interfere with the world or create miracles.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Some deists believe that a Divine Creator initiated a universe in which evolution occurred, by designing the system and the natural laws, although many deists believe that God also created life itself, before allowing it to be subject to evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] They find it to be undignified and unwieldy for a deity to make constant adjustments rather than letting evolution elegantly adapt organisms to changing environments.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] One recent convert to deism was philosopher and professor Antony Flew, who became a deist in December 2004.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Professor Flew, a former atheist, later argued that recent research into the origins of life supports the theory that some form of intelligence was involved.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Whilst accepting subsequent Darwinian evolution, Flew argued that this cannot explain the complexities of the origins of life.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Hindu views on evolution include a range of viewpoints with regard to evolution, creationism, and the origin of life within the traditions of Hinduism.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Some Hindu schools do not treat the scriptural creation myth literally and often the creation stories themselves do not go into specific detail, thus leaving open the possibility of incorporating at least some theories in support of evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Some Hindus find support for, or foreshadowing of evolutionary ideas in scriptures, namely the Vedas.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Science writers Carl Sagan and Fritjof Capra have pointed out similarities between the latest scientific understanding of the age of the universe, and the Hindu concept of a "day and night of Brahma", which is much closer to the current known age of the universe than other creation myths.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The days and nights of Brahma posit a view of the universe that is divinely created, and is not strictly evolutionary, but an ongoing cycle of birth, death, and rebirth of the universe.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The British geneticist and evolutionary biologist J B S Haldane observed that the Dasavataras (ten principal avatars of Lord Vishnu) provide a true sequential depiction of the great unfolding of evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The avatars of Vishnu show an uncanny similarity to the biological theory of evolution of life on earth.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Lord Rama, Lord Krishna and Lord Buddha were the seventh, eighth and ninth other avatars of Lord Vishnu.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] It indicates the physical and mental changes and evolution in the man from its time of appearance.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Although non-human evolution is not so controversial and a great amount of Muslims accept it, still a notable portion of Muslims disbelieve in origin of species from a common ancestor by evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Human evolution still stays quite controversial due to linking of modern humans with other non-human life forms which a lot of people argue that it goes against the special creation account of Adam and Eve as stated in the Qur'an.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Among those who accept evolution, many believe that humanity was a special creation by God.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] David Solomon Jalajel, an Islamic author, proclaims an Adamic exceptionalism view of evolution which encourages the theological use of *tawaqquf*; a *tawaqquf* is to make no argument for or against a matter to which scripture possesses no declarations for.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] With *tawaqquf*, Jalajel believes that Adam's creation does not necessarily signal the beginning of humanity as the Quran makes no declaration as to whether or not human beings were on Earth before Adam had descended.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Thus, the existence of Adam is a miracle since the Quran directly states it to be, but it does not assert there being no humans who could have existed at the time of Adam's appearance on earth and who could have came about as a result of evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] This viewpoint stands in contrast to creationism and human exceptionalism, ultimately declaring that evolution could be viewed without conflict with Islam and that Muslims could either accept or reject "human evolution on its scientific merits without reference to the story of Adam".
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Plenty of Muslims view that the theory of human evolution can be made compatible with the Islamic faith if the *homo* species which evolved from the Australopiths (such as *H.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Habilis, Rudolfensis, Erectus,* etc.) are viewed as mere *'pseudo-humans'* while Adam was the first *'true-human'* or just human in general.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Thus, it can be viewed that God created the first humans (true humans) who were Adam and Hawa through a miracle or special creation, while pseudo-humans were evolutionary creations of God.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Biologically similar or close living organisms can mate in a process known as hybridization.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Usually, the genetic similarities which allow hybridization is caused by having a very close common ancestor.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] However, since Adam and Hawa were special creations of God, that problem can be bypassed entirely because God can just create them with similar genetics.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Then, later descendants of Adam and Hawa (not even great grandchildren probably, but much later) met with the *pseudo-humans* and then hybridized with them.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The offspring of such a parent (a pre-hybridization true human and a pseudo-human) would be both a descendant of Adam and Hawa, as well as LUCA and all the other common ancestors in between; and the offspring would also be a true human.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] So, if such an event happened, all the human beings which came afterwards (including modern human beings) are simultaneously descendants of Adam and Hawa, as well as other common ancestors which evolutionary biologists theorize.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Adam and Hawa and their pre-hybridization descendants are considered as some kind of unknown human species whose fossils have not been found yet and thus, separate from the standard theory of evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] This retains the scientific consensus's view on how human evolution went (Erectus to Heidelbergensis, Heidelbergensis to Sapiens, etc.) without altering the already existing views while simply just considering one of the species among it were products of two species, not just one.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] This views science and religion as two independent sources of truth providing truths in their own fields which can be simultaneously compatible and believed in.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] So, there's no need for a conflict to exist.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Further evolution as planned by God may have happened after the hybridization and before hybridization among the descendants of Adam in such a way that they still stay true humans.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] This view is similar to Adamic exceptionalism.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] However, it has some theological differences which solves conflicts regarding Adam's identity as he is considered to be the first human.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] This view explains how Adam could've been the first human and the father of humanity even with some homo species being evolutionary products from other Genuses.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] This also explains how Adam's descendants were able to survive extreme genetic bottlenecking as hybridization would bring enough genetic varieties for survival with plenty of Muslims arguing that "God created the *pseudo-humans* through evolution only because of that.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] So, both true and pseudo humans serve or served a purpose".
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] This would also mean that Adam and Hawa and their descendants played a crucial role in shaping human evolution as hybridization would drastically change the future generations.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] So, human evolution would've gone into a completely different direction without them.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The Ahmadiyya movement universally accept the scientific principle of the process of evolution, with divine guidance.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Mirza Tahir Ahmad, the (late) leader of the Ahmadiyya movement, elaborated this by explaining the complex mechanism of evolution as having been played more like strategic game of chess rather than a random game of dice.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] In general, three of the four major denominations of American Judaism (Reconstructionist, Reform, and Conservative) accept theistic evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Within Orthodoxy, there is much debate about the issue.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Most Modern Orthodox groups accept theistic evolution and most Ultra-Orthodox groups do not.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] This disagreement was most vociferous in the Natan Slifkin controversy which arose when a number of prominent Ultra-Orthodox Rabbis banned books written by Rabbi Natan Slifkin which explored the idea of theistic evolution within Jewish tradition.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] These Rabbis forming part of Jewish opposition to evolution considered that his books were heresy as they indicated that the Talmud is not necessarily correct about scientific matters such as the age of the Earth.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Advocates of theistic evolution within Judaism follow two general approaches.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Either the creation account in the Torah is not to be taken as a literal text, but rather as a symbolic work, or, alternatively, that the 'days' do not refer to 24-hour periods.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The latter view, called day-age creationism, is justified by how the first day in the biblical account actually precedes the creation of the sun and earth by which 24-hour days are reckoned and by how the seventh day of rest has no evening and morning.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Karaite Judaism is a Jewish a movement which is distinct in that they do not accept the Talmud (a series of Rabbinic commentaries) as law and follow the Hebrew scriptures as they are written.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Karaites are currently divided on the question of evolution with many or most Karaite Jews leaning in favor of Theistic Evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] The Samaritans, a divergent branch of the Israelites (the other being the Jews), generally accept Theistic Evolution.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Samaritans do not consider themselves to be Jewish, but hold similar beliefs.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Pantheists (for instance in Naturalistic Pantheism) may view natural processes, including evolution, as work or emanations from the impersonal, non-anthropomorphic deity.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Although evolutionary biologists have often been agnostics (most notably Thomas Huxley and Charles Darwin) or atheists (most notably Richard Dawkins), from the outset many have had a belief in some form of theism.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] These have included Alfred Russel Wallace, who in a joint paper with Charles Darwin in 1858, proposed the theory of evolution by natural selection.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Wallace, in his later years, was effectively a deist who believed that "the unseen universe of Spirit" had interceded to create life as well as consciousness in animals and separately in humans.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Darwin had a longstanding close friendship with the American botanist Asa Gray who was a leading supporter of Darwin's theory, and a devout Presbyterian.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Gray wrote a series of essays on the relationship of natural selection to religious belief and natural theology, and supported the views of theologians who said that design through evolution was inherent in all forms of life.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Darwin had Gray and Charles Kingsley in mind when he wrote that "It seems to me absurd to doubt that a man may be an ardent theist & an evolutionist".
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Pierre Teilhard de Chardin (1881–1955) was a noted geologist and paleontologist as well as a Jesuit Priest who wrote extensively on the subject of incorporating evolution into a new understanding of Christianity.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Initially suppressed by the Roman Catholic Church, his theological work has had considerable influence and is widely taught in Catholic and most mainline Protestant seminaries.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Both Ronald Fisher (1890–1962) and Theodosius Dobzhansky (1900–1975), were Christians and architects of the modern evolutionary synthesis.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] "I am a creationist and an evolutionist.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Evolution is God's, or Nature's, method of creation.
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Creation is not an event that happened in 4004 BC; it is a process that began some 10 billion years ago and is still under way...
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] Does the evolutionary doctrine clash with religious faith?
[src:evolution/acceptance-of-evolution-by-religious-groups] It is a blunder to mistake the Holy Scriptures for elementary textbooks of astronomy, geology, biology, and anthropology.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:evolution/acidobacteriota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
[src:evolution/actinomycetota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The scientific theory of evolution by natural selection was conceived independently by two British naturalists, Charles Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace, in the mid-19th century as an explanation for why organisms are adapted to their physical and biological environments.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The theory was first set out in detail in Darwin's book *On the Origin of Species*.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In successive generations, members of a population are therefore more likely to be replaced by the offspring of parents with favourable characteristics for that environment.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In the early 20th century, competing ideas of evolution were refuted and evolution was combined with Mendelian inheritance and population genetics to give rise to modern evolutionary theory.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In this synthesis the basis for heredity is in DNA molecules that pass information from generation to generation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The processes that change DNA in a population include natural selection, genetic drift, mutation, and gene flow.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] All life on Earth—including humanity—shares a last universal common ancestor (LUCA), which lived approximately 3.5–3.8 billion years ago.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The fossil record includes a progression from early biogenic graphite to microbial mat fossils to fossilised multicellular organisms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Existing patterns of biodiversity have been shaped by repeated formations of new species (speciation), changes within species (anagenesis), and loss of species (extinction) throughout the evolutionary history of life on Earth.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Morphological and biochemical traits tend to be more similar among species that share a more recent common ancestor, which historically was used to reconstruct phylogenetic trees, although direct comparison of genetic sequences is a more common method today.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Evolutionary biologists have continued to study various aspects of evolution by forming and testing hypotheses as well as constructing theories based on evidence from the field or laboratory and on data generated by the methods of mathematical and theoretical biology.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Their discoveries have influenced not just the development of biology but also other fields including agriculture, medicine, and computer science.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Evolution in organisms occurs through changes in heritable characteristics—the inherited characteristics of an organism.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In humans, for example, eye colour is an inherited characteristic and an individual might inherit the "brown-eye trait" from one of their parents.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Inherited traits are controlled by genes and the complete set of genes within an organism's genome (genetic material) is called its *genotype*.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The complete set of observable traits that make up the structure and behaviour of an organism is called its *phenotype*.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Some of these traits come from the interaction of its genotype with the environment while others are neutral.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Some observable characteristics are not inherited.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] For example, suntanned skin comes from the interaction between a person's genotype and sunlight; thus, suntans are not passed on to people's children.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The phenotype is the ability of the skin to tan when exposed to sunlight.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] However, some people tan more easily than others, due to differences in genotypic variation; a striking example are people with the inherited trait of albinism, who do not tan at all and are very sensitive to sunburn.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Heritable characteristics are passed from one generation to the next via DNA, a molecule that encodes genetic information.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] DNA is a long biopolymer composed of four types of bases.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The sequence of bases along a particular DNA molecule specifies the genetic information, in a manner similar to a sequence of letters spelling out a sentence.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Before a cell divides, the DNA is copied, so that each of the resulting two cells will inherit the DNA sequence.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Portions of a DNA molecule that specify a single functional unit are called genes; different genes have different sequences of bases.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Within cells, each long strand of DNA is called a chromosome.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The specific location of a DNA sequence within a chromosome is known as a locus.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] If the DNA sequence at a locus varies between individuals, the different forms of this sequence are called alleles.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] DNA sequences can change through mutations, producing new alleles.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] If a mutation occurs within a gene, the new allele may affect the trait that the gene controls, altering the phenotype of the organism.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] However, while this simple correspondence between an allele and a trait works in some cases, most traits are influenced by multiple genes in a quantitative or epistatic manner.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Evolution can occur if there is genetic variation within a population.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Variation comes from mutations in the genome, reshuffling of genes through sexual reproduction and migration between populations (gene flow).
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Despite the constant introduction of new variation through mutation and gene flow, most of the genome of a species is very similar among all individuals of that species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] However, discoveries in the field of evolutionary developmental biology have demonstrated that even relatively small differences in genotype can lead to dramatic differences in phenotype both within and between species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] An individual organism's phenotype results from both its genotype and the influence of the environment it has lived in.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The modern evolutionary synthesis defines evolution as the change over time in this genetic variation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The frequency of one particular allele will become more or less prevalent relative to other forms of that gene.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Variation disappears when a new allele reaches the point of fixation—when it either disappears from the population or replaces the ancestral allele entirely.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Mutations are changes in the DNA sequence of a cell's genome and are the ultimate source of genetic variation in all organisms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] When mutations occur, they may alter the product of a gene, or prevent the gene from functioning, or have no effect.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] About half of the mutations in the coding regions of protein-coding genes are deleterious — the other half are neutral.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] A small percentage of the total mutations in this region confer a fitness benefit.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Some of the mutations in other parts of the genome are deleterious but the vast majority are neutral.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Mutations can involve large sections of a chromosome becoming duplicated (usually by genetic recombination), which can introduce extra copies of a gene into a genome.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Extra copies of genes are a major source of the raw material needed for new genes to evolve.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This is important because most new genes evolve within gene families from pre-existing genes that share common ancestors.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] For example, the human eye uses four genes to make structures that sense light: three for colour vision and one for night vision; all four are descended from a single ancestral gene.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] New genes can be generated from an ancestral gene when a duplicate copy mutates and acquires a new function.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This process is easier once a gene has been duplicated because it increases the redundancy of the system; one gene in the pair can acquire a new function while the other copy continues to perform its original function.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Other types of mutations can even generate entirely new genes from previously noncoding DNA, a phenomenon termed *de novo* gene birth.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The generation of new genes can also involve small parts of several genes being duplicated, with these fragments then recombining to form new combinations with new functions (exon shuffling).
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] When new genes are assembled from shuffling pre-existing parts, domains act as modules with simple independent functions, which can be mixed together to produce new combinations with new and complex functions.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] For example, polyketide synthases are large enzymes that make antibiotics; they contain up to 100 independent domains that each catalyse one step in the overall process, like a step in an assembly line.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] One example of mutation is wild boar piglets.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] They are camouflage coloured and show a characteristic pattern of dark and light longitudinal stripes.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] However, mutations in the *melanocortin 1 receptor* (*MC1R*) disrupt the pattern.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The majority of pig breeds carry MC1R mutations disrupting wild-type colour and different mutations causing dominant black colouring.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In asexual organisms, genes are inherited together, or *linked*, as they cannot mix with genes of other organisms during reproduction.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In contrast, the offspring of sexual organisms contain random mixtures of their parents' chromosomes that are produced through independent assortment.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In a related process called homologous recombination, sexual organisms exchange DNA between two matching chromosomes.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Recombination and reassortment do not alter allele frequencies, but instead change which alleles are associated with each other, producing offspring with new combinations of alleles.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Sex usually increases genetic variation and may increase the rate of evolution.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The two-fold cost of sex was first described by John Maynard Smith.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The first cost is that in sexually dimorphic species only one of the two sexes can bear young.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This cost does not apply to hermaphroditic species, like most plants and many invertebrates.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The second cost is that any individual who reproduces sexually can only pass on 50% of its genes to any individual offspring, with even less passed on as each new generation passes.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Yet sexual reproduction is the more common means of reproduction among eukaryotes and multicellular organisms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The Red Queen hypothesis has been used to explain the significance of sexual reproduction as a means to enable continual evolution and adaptation in response to coevolution with other species in an ever-changing environment.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Another hypothesis is that sexual reproduction is primarily an adaptation for promoting accurate recombinational repair of damage in germline DNA, and that increased diversity is a byproduct of this process that may sometimes be adaptively beneficial.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Gene flow is the exchange of genes between populations and between species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] It can therefore be a source of variation that is new to a population or to a species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Gene flow can be caused by the movement of individuals between separate populations of organisms, as might be caused by the movement of mice between inland and coastal populations, or the movement of pollen between heavy-metal-tolerant and heavy-metal-sensitive populations of grasses.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Gene transfer between species includes the formation of hybrid organisms and horizontal gene transfer.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Horizontal gene transfer is the transfer of genetic material from one organism to another organism that is not its offspring; this is most common among bacteria.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In medicine, this contributes to the spread of antibiotic resistance, as when one bacteria acquires resistance genes it can rapidly transfer them to other species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Horizontal transfer of genes from bacteria to eukaryotes such as the yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* and the adzuki bean weevil *Callosobruchus chinensis* has occurred.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] An example of larger-scale transfers are the eukaryotic bdelloid rotifers, which have received a range of genes from bacteria, fungi and plants.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Viruses can also carry DNA between organisms, allowing transfer of genes even across biological domains.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Large-scale gene transfer has also occurred between the ancestors of eukaryotic cells and bacteria, during the acquisition of chloroplasts and mitochondria.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] It is possible that eukaryotes themselves originated from horizontal gene transfers between bacteria and archaea.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Some heritable changes cannot be explained by changes to the sequence of nucleotides in the DNA.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] These phenomena are classed as epigenetic inheritance systems.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] DNA methylation marking chromatin, self-sustaining metabolic loops, gene silencing by RNA interference and the three-dimensional conformation of proteins (such as prions) are areas where epigenetic inheritance systems have been discovered at the organismic level.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Developmental biologists suggest that complex interactions in genetic networks and communication among cells can lead to heritable variations that may underlay some of the mechanics in developmental plasticity and canalisation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Heritability may also occur at even larger scales.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] For example, ecological inheritance through the process of niche construction is defined by the regular and repeated activities of organisms in their environment.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This generates a legacy of effects that modify and feed back into the selection regime of subsequent generations.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Other examples of heritability in evolution that are not under the direct control of genes include the inheritance of cultural traits and symbiogenesis.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] From a neo-Darwinian perspective, evolution occurs when there are changes in the frequencies of alleles within a population of interbreeding organisms, for example, the allele for black colour in a population of moths becoming more common.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Mechanisms that can lead to changes in allele frequencies include natural selection, genetic drift, and mutation bias.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Evolution by natural selection is the process by which traits that enhance survival and reproduction become more common in successive generations of a population.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] More offspring are produced than can possibly survive, and these conditions produce competition between organisms for survival and reproduction.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Consequently, organisms with traits that give them an advantage over their competitors are more likely to pass on their traits to the next generation than those with traits that do not confer an advantage.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This teleonomy is the quality whereby the process of natural selection creates and preserves traits that are seemingly fitted for the functional roles they perform.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Consequences of selection include nonrandom mating and genetic hitchhiking.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The central concept of natural selection is the evolutionary fitness of an organism.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Fitness is measured by an organism's ability to survive and reproduce, which determines the size of its genetic contribution to the next generation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] However, fitness is not the same as the total number of offspring: instead fitness is indicated by the proportion of subsequent generations that carry an organism's genes.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] For example, if an organism could survive well and reproduce rapidly, but its offspring were all too small and weak to survive, this organism would make little genetic contribution to future generations and would thus have low fitness.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] If an allele increases fitness more than the other alleles of that gene, then with each generation this allele has a higher probability of becoming common within the population.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] These traits are said to be selected *for*.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Examples of traits that can increase fitness are enhanced survival and increased fecundity.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Conversely, the lower fitness caused by having a less beneficial or deleterious allele results in this allele likely becoming rarer—they are selected *against*.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Importantly, the fitness of an allele is not a fixed characteristic; if the environment changes, previously neutral or harmful traits may become beneficial and previously beneficial traits become harmful.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] However, even if the direction of selection does reverse in this way, traits that were lost in the past may not re-evolve in an identical form.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] "Throwbacks" such as these are known as atavisms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Natural selection within a population for a trait that can vary across a range of values, such as height, can be categorised into three different types.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The first is directional selection, which is a shift in the average value of a trait over time—for example, organisms slowly getting taller.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Secondly, disruptive selection is selection for extreme trait values and often results in two different values becoming most common, with selection against the average value.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This would be when either short or tall organisms had an advantage, but not those of medium height.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Finally, in stabilising selection there is selection against extreme trait values on both ends, which causes a decrease in variance around the average value and less diversity.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This would, for example, cause organisms to eventually have a similar height.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Natural selection most generally makes nature the measure against which individuals and individual traits, are more or less likely to survive.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] "Nature" in this sense refers to an ecosystem, that is, a system in which organisms interact with every other element, physical as well as biological, in their local environment.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] These relationships involve the life history of the organism, its position in the food chain and its geographic range.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This broad understanding of nature enables scientists to delineate specific forces which, together, comprise natural selection.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Natural selection can act at different levels of organisation, such as genes, cells, individual organisms, groups of organisms and species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Selection can act at multiple levels simultaneously.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] An example of selection occurring below the level of the individual organism are genes called transposons, which can replicate and spread throughout a genome.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Selection at a level above the individual, such as group selection, may allow the evolution of cooperation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Genetic drift is the random fluctuation of allele frequencies within a population from one generation to the next.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] When selective forces are absent or relatively weak, allele frequencies are equally likely to *drift* upward or downward in each successive generation because the alleles are subject to sampling error.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This drift halts when an allele eventually becomes fixed, either by disappearing from the population or by replacing the other alleles entirely.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Genetic drift may therefore eliminate some alleles from a population due to chance alone.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Even in the absence of selective forces, genetic drift can cause two separate populations that begin with the same genetic structure to drift apart into two divergent populations with different sets of alleles.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] According to the neutral theory of molecular evolution most evolutionary changes are the result of the fixation of neutral mutations by genetic drift.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In this model, most genetic changes in a population are thus the result of constant mutation pressure and genetic drift.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This form of the neutral theory has been debated since it does not seem to fit some genetic variation seen in nature.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] A better-supported version of this model is the nearly neutral theory, according to which a mutation that would be effectively neutral in a small population is not necessarily neutral in a large population.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Other theories propose that genetic drift is dwarfed by other stochastic forces in evolution, such as genetic hitchhiking, also known as genetic draft.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The time it takes a neutral allele to become fixed by genetic drift depends on population size; fixation is more rapid in smaller populations.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The number of individuals in a population is not critical, but instead a measure known as the effective population size.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The effective population is usually smaller than the total population since it takes into account factors such as the level of inbreeding and the stage of the lifecycle in which the population is the smallest.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The effective population size may not be the same for every gene in the same population.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] It is usually difficult to measure the relative importance of selection and neutral processes, including drift.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The comparative importance of adaptive and non-adaptive forces in driving evolutionary change is an area of current research.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Mutation bias is usually conceived as a difference in expected rates for two different kinds of mutation, e.g., transition-transversion bias, GC-AT bias, deletion-insertion bias.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This is related to the idea of developmental bias.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Haldane and Ronald Fisher argued that, because mutation is a weak pressure easily overcome by selection, tendencies of mutation would be ineffectual except under conditions of neutral evolution or extraordinarily high mutation rates.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This opposing-pressures argument was long used to dismiss the possibility of internal tendencies in evolution, until the molecular era prompted renewed interest in neutral evolution.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Noboru Sueoka and Ernst Freese proposed that systematic biases in mutation might be responsible for systematic differences in genomic GC composition between species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The identification of a GC-biased *E. coli* mutator strain in 1967, along with the proposal of the neutral theory, established the plausibility of mutational explanations for molecular patterns, which are now common in the molecular evolution literature.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] For instance, mutation biases are frequently invoked in models of codon usage.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Such models also include effects of selection, following the mutation-selection-drift model, which allows both for mutation biases and differential selection based on effects on translation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Hypotheses of mutation bias have played an important role in the development of thinking about the evolution of genome composition, including isochores.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Different insertion vs. deletion biases in different taxa can lead to the evolution of different genome sizes.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The hypothesis of Lynch regarding genome size relies on mutational biases toward increase or decrease in genome size.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] However, mutational hypotheses for the evolution of composition suffered a reduction in scope when it was discovered that (1) GC-biased gene conversion makes an important contribution to composition in diploid organisms such as mammals and (2) bacterial genomes frequently have AT-biased mutation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Contemporary thinking about the role of mutation biases reflects a different theory from that of Haldane and Fisher.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Several studies report that the mutations implicated in adaptation reflect common mutation biases though others dispute this interpretation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Recombination allows alleles on the same strand of DNA to become separated.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] However, the rate of recombination is low (approximately two events per chromosome per generation).
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] As a result, genes close together on a chromosome may not always be shuffled away from each other and genes that are close together tend to be inherited together, a phenomenon known as linkage.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This tendency is measured by finding how often two alleles occur together on a single chromosome compared to expectations, which is called their linkage disequilibrium.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] A set of alleles that is usually inherited in a group is called a haplotype.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This can be important when one allele in a particular haplotype is strongly beneficial: natural selection can drive a selective sweep that will also cause the other alleles in the haplotype to become more common in the population; this effect is called genetic hitchhiking or genetic draft.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Genetic draft caused by the fact that some neutral genes are genetically linked to others that are under selection can be partially captured by an appropriate effective population size.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] A special case of natural selection is sexual selection, which is selection for any trait that increases mating success by increasing the attractiveness of an organism to potential mates.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Traits that evolved through sexual selection are particularly prominent among males of several animal species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Although sexually favoured, traits such as cumbersome antlers, mating calls, large body size and bright colours often attract predation, which compromises the survival of individual males.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This survival disadvantage is balanced by higher reproductive success in males that show these hard-to-fake, sexually selected traits.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Evolution influences every aspect of the form and behaviour of organisms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Most prominent are the specific behavioural and physical adaptations that are the outcome of natural selection.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] These adaptations increase fitness by aiding activities such as finding food, avoiding predators or attracting mates.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Organisms can also respond to selection by cooperating with each other, usually by aiding their relatives or engaging in mutually beneficial symbiosis.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In the longer term, evolution produces new species through splitting ancestral populations of organisms into new groups that cannot or will not interbreed.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] These outcomes of evolution are distinguished based on time scale as macroevolution versus microevolution.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Macroevolution refers to evolution that occurs at or above the level of species, in particular speciation and extinction, whereas microevolution refers to smaller evolutionary changes within a species or population, in particular shifts in allele frequency and adaptation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Macroevolution is the outcome of long periods of microevolution.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Thus, the distinction between micro- and macroevolution is not a fundamental one—the difference is simply the time involved.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] However, in macroevolution, the traits of the entire species may be important.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] For instance, a large amount of variation among individuals allows a species to rapidly adapt to new habitats, lessening the chance of it going extinct, while a wide geographic range increases the chance of speciation, by making it more likely that part of the population will become isolated.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In this sense, microevolution and macroevolution might involve selection at different levels—with microevolution acting on genes and organisms, versus macroevolutionary processes such as species selection acting on entire species and affecting their rates of speciation and extinction.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] A common misconception is that evolution has goals, long-term plans, or an innate tendency for "progress", as expressed in beliefs such as orthogenesis and evolutionism; realistically, however, evolution has no long-term goal and does not necessarily produce greater complexity.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Although complex species have evolved, they occur as a side effect of the overall number of organisms increasing, and simple forms of life still remain more common in the biosphere.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] For example, the overwhelming majority of species are microscopic prokaryotes, which form about half the world's biomass despite their small size and constitute the vast majority of Earth's biodiversity.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Simple organisms have therefore been the dominant form of life on Earth throughout its history and continue to be the main form of life up to the present day, with complex life only appearing more diverse because it is more noticeable.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Indeed, the evolution of microorganisms is particularly important to evolutionary research since their rapid reproduction allows the study of experimental evolution and the observation of evolution and adaptation in real time.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Adaptation is the process that makes organisms better suited to their habitat.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Also, the term adaptation may refer to a trait that is important for an organism's survival.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] For example, the adaptation of horses' teeth to the grinding of grass.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] By using the term *adaptation* for the evolutionary process and *adaptive trait* for the product (the bodily part or function), the two senses of the word may be distinguished.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Adaptations are produced by natural selection.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] *Adaptedness* is the state of being adapted: the degree to which an organism is able to live and reproduce in a given set of habitats.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] An *adaptive trait* is an aspect of the developmental pattern of the organism which enables or enhances the probability of that organism surviving and reproducing.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Adaptation may cause either the gain of a new feature, or the loss of an ancestral feature.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] An example that shows both types of change is bacterial adaptation to antibiotic selection, with genetic changes causing antibiotic resistance by both modifying the target of the drug, or increasing the activity of transporters that pump the drug out of the cell.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] An interesting but still controversial idea is that some adaptations might increase the ability of organisms to generate genetic diversity and adapt by natural selection (increasing organisms' evolvability).
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Adaptation occurs through the gradual modification of existing structures.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Consequently, structures with similar internal organisation may have different functions in related organisms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This is the result of a single ancestral structure being adapted to function in different ways.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The bones within bat wings, for example, are very similar to those in mice feet and primate hands, due to the descent of all these structures from a common mammalian ancestor.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] During evolution, some structures may lose their original function and become vestigial structures.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Such structures may have little or no function in a current species, yet have a clear function in ancestral species, or other closely related species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Examples include pseudogenes, the non-functional remains of eyes in blind cave-dwelling fish, wings in flightless birds, the presence of hip bones in whales and snakes, and sexual traits in organisms that reproduce via asexual reproduction.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Examples of vestigial structures in humans include wisdom teeth, the coccyx, the vermiform appendix, and other behavioural vestiges such as goose bumps and primitive reflexes.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] However, many traits that appear to be simple adaptations are in fact exaptations: structures originally adapted for one function, but which coincidentally became somewhat useful for some other function in the process.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] One example is the African lizard *Holaspis guentheri*, which developed an extremely flat head for hiding in crevices, as can be seen by looking at its near relatives.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] However, in this species, the head has become so flattened that it assists in gliding from tree to tree—an exaptation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Within cells, molecular machines such as the bacterial flagella and protein sorting machinery evolved by the recruitment of several pre-existing proteins that previously had different functions.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Another example is the recruitment of enzymes from glycolysis and xenobiotic metabolism to serve as structural proteins called crystallins within the lenses of organisms' eyes.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] An area of current investigation in evolutionary developmental biology is the developmental basis of adaptations and exaptations.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This research addresses the origin and evolution of embryonic development and how modifications of development and developmental processes produce novel features.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] These studies have shown that evolution can alter development to produce new structures, such as embryonic bone structures that develop into the jaw in other animals instead forming part of the middle ear in mammals.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] It is also possible for structures that have been lost in evolution to reappear due to changes in developmental genes, such as a mutation in chickens causing embryos to grow teeth similar to those of crocodiles.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] It is now becoming clear that most alterations in the form of organisms are due to changes in a small set of conserved genes.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Interactions between organisms can produce both conflict and cooperation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] When the interaction is between pairs of species, such as a pathogen and a host, or a predator and its prey, these species can develop matched sets of adaptations.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Here, the evolution of one species causes adaptations in a second species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] These changes in the second species then, in turn, cause new adaptations in the first species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This cycle of selection and response is called coevolution.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] An example is the production of tetrodotoxin in the rough-skinned newt and the evolution of tetrodotoxin resistance in its predator, the common garter snake.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In this predator-prey pair, an evolutionary arms race has produced high levels of toxin in the newt and correspondingly high levels of toxin resistance in the snake.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Not all co-evolved interactions between species involve conflict.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Many cases of mutually beneficial interactions have evolved.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] For instance, an extreme cooperation exists between plants and the mycorrhizal fungi that grow on their roots and aid the plant in absorbing nutrients from the soil.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This is a reciprocal relationship as the plants provide the fungi with sugars from photosynthesis.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Here, the fungi actually grow inside plant cells, allowing them to exchange nutrients with their hosts, while sending signals that suppress the plant immune system.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Coalitions between organisms of the same species have also evolved.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] An extreme case is the eusociality found in social insects, such as bees, termites and ants, where sterile insects feed and guard the small number of organisms in a colony that are able to reproduce.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] On an even smaller scale, the somatic cells that make up the body of an animal limit their reproduction so they can maintain a stable organism, which then supports a small number of the animal's germ cells to produce offspring.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Here, somatic cells respond to specific signals that instruct them whether to grow, remain as they are, or die.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] If cells ignore these signals and multiply inappropriately, their uncontrolled growth causes cancer.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Such cooperation within species may have evolved through the process of kin selection, which is where one organism acts to help raise a relative's offspring.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This activity is selected for because if the *helping* individual contains alleles which promote the helping activity, it is likely that its kin will *also* contain these alleles and thus those alleles will be passed on.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Other processes that may promote cooperation include group selection, where cooperation provides benefits to a group of organisms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Speciation is the process where a species diverges into two or more descendant species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] There are multiple ways to define the concept of "species".
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The choice of definition is dependent on the particularities of the species concerned.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] For example, some species concepts apply more readily toward sexually reproducing organisms while others lend themselves better toward asexual organisms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Despite the diversity of various species concepts, these various concepts can be placed into one of three broad philosophical approaches: interbreeding, ecological and phylogenetic.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The Biological Species Concept (BSC) is a classic example of the interbreeding approach.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Some researchers have attempted a unifying monistic definition of species, while others adopt a pluralistic approach and suggest that there may be different ways to logically interpret the definition of a species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Barriers to reproduction between two diverging sexual populations are required for the populations to become new species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Gene flow may slow this process by spreading the new genetic variants also to the other populations.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Depending on how far two species have diverged since their most recent common ancestor, it may still be possible for them to produce offspring, as with horses and donkeys mating to produce mules.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In this case, closely related species may regularly interbreed, but hybrids will be selected against and the species will remain distinct.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] However, viable hybrids are occasionally formed and these new species can either have properties intermediate between their parent species, or possess a totally new phenotype.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The importance of hybridisation in producing new species of animals is unclear, although cases have been seen in many types of animals, with the grey tree frog being a particularly well-studied example.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Speciation has been observed multiple times under both controlled laboratory conditions and in nature.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In sexually reproducing organisms, speciation results from reproductive isolation followed by genealogical divergence.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] There are four primary geographic modes of speciation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The most common in animals is allopatric speciation, which occurs in populations initially isolated geographically, such as by habitat fragmentation or migration.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Selection under these conditions can produce very rapid changes in the appearance and behaviour of organisms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] As selection and drift act independently on populations isolated from the rest of their species, separation may eventually produce organisms that cannot interbreed.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The second mode of speciation is peripatric speciation, which occurs when small populations of organisms become isolated in a new environment.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This differs from allopatric speciation in that the isolated populations are numerically much smaller than the parental population.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Here, the founder effect causes rapid speciation after an increase in inbreeding increases selection on homozygotes, leading to rapid genetic change.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The third mode is parapatric speciation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This is similar to peripatric speciation in that a small population enters a new habitat, but differs in that there is no physical separation between these two populations.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Instead, speciation results from the evolution of mechanisms that reduce gene flow between the two populations.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Generally this occurs when there has been a drastic change in the environment within the parental species' habitat.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] One example is the grass *Anthoxanthum odoratum*, which can undergo parapatric speciation in response to localised metal pollution from mines.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Here, plants evolve that have resistance to high levels of metals in the soil.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Selection against interbreeding with the metal-sensitive parental population produced a gradual change in the flowering time of the metal-resistant plants, which eventually produced complete reproductive isolation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Selection against hybrids between the two populations may cause reinforcement, which is the evolution of traits that promote mating within a species, as well as character displacement, which is when two species become more distinct in appearance.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Finally, in sympatric speciation species diverge without geographic isolation or changes in habitat.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This form is rare since even a small amount of gene flow may remove genetic differences between parts of a population.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Generally, sympatric speciation in animals requires the evolution of both genetic differences and nonrandom mating, to allow reproductive isolation to evolve.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] One type of sympatric speciation involves crossbreeding of two related species to produce a new hybrid species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This is not common in animals as animal hybrids are usually sterile.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This is because during meiosis the homologous chromosomes from each parent are from different species and cannot successfully pair.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] However, it is more common in plants because plants often double their number of chromosomes, to form polyploids.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This allows the chromosomes from each parental species to form matching pairs during meiosis, since each parent's chromosomes are represented by a pair already.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] An example of such a speciation event is when the plant species *Arabidopsis thaliana* and *Arabidopsis arenosa* crossbred to give the new species *Arabidopsis suecica*.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] This happened about 20,000 years ago, and the speciation process has been repeated in the laboratory, which allows the study of the genetic mechanisms involved in this process.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Indeed, chromosome doubling within a species may be a common cause of reproductive isolation, as half the doubled chromosomes will be unmatched when breeding with undoubled organisms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Speciation events are important in the theory of punctuated equilibrium, which accounts for the pattern in the fossil record of short "bursts" of evolution interspersed with relatively long periods of stasis, where species remain relatively unchanged.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] In this theory, speciation and rapid evolution are linked, with natural selection and genetic drift acting most strongly on organisms undergoing speciation in novel habitats or small populations.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] As a result, the periods of stasis in the fossil record correspond to the parental population and the organisms undergoing speciation and rapid evolution are found in small populations or geographically restricted habitats and therefore rarely being preserved as fossils.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Extinction is the disappearance of an entire species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Extinction is not an unusual event, as species regularly appear through speciation and disappear through extinction.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Nearly all animal and plant species that have lived on Earth are now extinct, and extinction appears to be the ultimate fate of all species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] These extinctions have happened continuously throughout the history of life, although the rate of extinction spikes in occasional mass extinction events.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, during which the non-avian dinosaurs became extinct, is the most well-known, but the earlier Permian–Triassic extinction event was even more severe, with approximately 96% of all marine species driven to extinction.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The Holocene extinction event is an ongoing mass extinction associated with humanity's expansion across the globe over the past few thousand years.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Present-day extinction rates are 100–1000 times greater than the background rate and up to 30% of current species may be extinct by the mid 21st century.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Human activities are now the primary cause of the ongoing extinction event; global warming may further accelerate it in the future.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] Despite the estimated extinction of more than 99% of all species that ever lived on Earth, about 1 trillion species are estimated to be on Earth currently with only one-thousandth of 1% described.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The role of extinction in evolution is not very well understood and may depend on which type of extinction is considered.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The causes of the continuous "low-level" extinction events, which form the majority of extinctions, may be the result of competition between species for limited resources (the competitive exclusion principle).
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] If one species can out-compete another, this could produce species selection, with the fitter species surviving and the other species being driven to extinction.
[src:evolution/evolution-p01] The intermittent mass extinctions are also important, but instead of acting as a selective force, they drastically reduce diversity in a nonspecific manner and promote bursts of rapid evolution and speciation in survivors.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Concepts and models used in evolutionary biology, such as natural selection, have many applications.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Artificial selection is the intentional selection of traits in a population of organisms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] This has been used for thousands of years in the domestication of plants and animals.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] More recently, such selection has become a vital part of genetic engineering, with selectable markers such as antibiotic resistance genes being used to manipulate DNA.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Proteins with valuable properties have evolved by repeated rounds of mutation and selection (for example modified enzymes and new antibodies) in a process called directed evolution.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Understanding the changes that have occurred during an organism's evolution can reveal the genes needed to construct parts of the body, genes which may be involved in human genetic disorders.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] For example, the Mexican tetra is an albino cavefish that lost its eyesight during evolution.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Breeding together different populations of this blind fish produced some offspring with functional eyes, since different mutations had occurred in the isolated populations that had evolved in different caves.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] This helped identify genes required for vision and pigmentation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Evolutionary theory has many applications in medicine.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Many human diseases are not static phenomena, but capable of evolution.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Viruses, bacteria, fungi and cancers evolve to be resistant to host immune defences, as well as to pharmaceutical drugs.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] These same problems occur in agriculture with pesticide and herbicide resistance.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In computer science, simulations of evolution using evolutionary algorithms and artificial life started in the 1960s and were extended with simulation of artificial selection.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Artificial evolution became a widely recognised optimisation method as a result of the work of Ingo Rechenberg in the 1960s.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] He used evolution strategies to solve complex engineering problems.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Genetic algorithms in particular became popular through the writing of John Henry Holland.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Practical applications also include automatic evolution of computer programmes.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Evolutionary algorithms are now used to solve multi-dimensional problems more efficiently than software produced by human designers and also to optimise the design of systems.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The Earth is about 4.54 billion years old.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The earliest undisputed evidence of life on Earth dates from at least 3.5 billion years ago, during the Eoarchean Era after a geological crust started to solidify following the earlier molten Hadean Eon.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Microbial mat fossils have been found in 3.48 billion-year-old sandstone in Western Australia.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Other early physical evidence of a biogenic substance is graphite in 3.7 billion-year-old metasedimentary rocks discovered in Western Greenland as well as "remains of biotic life" found in 4.1 billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Commenting on the Australian findings, Stephen Blair Hedges wrote: "If life arose relatively quickly on Earth, then it could be common in the universe." In July 2016, scientists reported identifying a set of 355 genes from the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all organisms living on Earth.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] More than 99% of all species, amounting to over five billion species, that ever lived on Earth are estimated to be extinct.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Estimates on the number of Earth's current species range from 10 million to 14 million, of which about 1.9 million are estimated to have been named and 1.6 million documented in a central database to date, leaving at least 80% not yet described.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Highly energetic chemistry is thought to have produced a self-replicating molecule around 4 billion years ago, and half a billion years later the last common ancestor of all life existed.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The current scientific consensus is that the complex biochemistry that makes up life came from simpler chemical reactions.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The beginning of life may have included self-replicating molecules such as RNA and the assembly of simple cells.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] All organisms on Earth are descended from a common ancestor or ancestral gene pool.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Current species are a stage in the process of evolution, with their diversity the product of a long series of speciation and extinction events.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The common descent of organisms was first deduced from four simple facts about organisms: First, they have geographic distributions that cannot be explained by local adaptation.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Second, the diversity of life is not a set of completely unique organisms, but organisms that share morphological similarities.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Third, vestigial traits with no clear purpose resemble functional ancestral traits.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Fourth, organisms can be classified using these similarities into a hierarchy of nested groups, similar to a family tree.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Due to horizontal gene transfer, this "tree of life" may be more complicated than a simple branching tree, since some genes have spread independently between distantly related species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] To solve this problem and others, some authors prefer to use the "Coral of life" as a metaphor or a mathematical model to illustrate the evolution of life.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] This view dates back to an idea briefly mentioned by Darwin but later abandoned.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Past species have also left records of their evolutionary history.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Fossils, along with the comparative anatomy of present-day organisms, constitute the morphological, or anatomical, record.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] By comparing the anatomies of both modern and extinct species, palaeontologists can infer the lineages of those species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] However, this approach is most successful for organisms that had hard body parts, such as shells, bones or teeth.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Further, as prokaryotes such as bacteria and archaea share a limited set of common morphologies, their fossils do not provide information on their ancestry.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] More recently, evidence for common descent has come from the study of biochemical similarities between organisms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] For example, all living cells use the same basic set of nucleotides and amino acids.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The development of molecular genetics has revealed the record of evolution left in organisms' genomes: dating when species diverged through the molecular clock produced by mutations.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] For example, these DNA sequence comparisons have revealed that humans and chimpanzees share 98% of their genomes and analysing the few areas where they differ helps shed light on when the common ancestor of these species existed.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Prokaryotes inhabited the Earth from approximately 3–4 billion years ago.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] No obvious changes in morphology or cellular organisation occurred in these organisms over the next few billion years.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The eukaryotic cells emerged between 1.6 and 2.7 billion years ago.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The next major change in cell structure came when bacteria were engulfed by eukaryotic cells, in a cooperative association called endosymbiosis.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The engulfed bacteria and the host cell then underwent coevolution, with the bacteria evolving into either mitochondria or hydrogenosomes.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Another engulfment of cyanobacterial-like organisms led to the formation of chloroplasts in algae and plants.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The history of life was that of the unicellular eukaryotes, prokaryotes and archaea until around 1.7 billion years ago, when multicellular organisms began to appear, with differentiated cells performing specialised functions.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The evolution of multicellularity occurred in multiple independent events, in organisms as diverse as sponges, brown algae, cyanobacteria, slime moulds and myxobacteria.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In January 2016, scientists reported that, about 800 million years ago, a minor genetic change in a single molecule called GK-PID may have allowed organisms to go from a single cell organism to one of many cells.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Approximately 538.8 million years ago, a remarkable amount of biological diversity appeared over a span of around 10 million years in what is called the Cambrian explosion.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Here, the majority of types of modern animals appeared in the fossil record, as well as unique lineages that subsequently became extinct.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Various triggers for the Cambrian explosion have been proposed, including the accumulation of oxygen in the atmosphere from photosynthesis.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] About 500 million years ago, plants and fungi colonised the land and were soon followed by arthropods and other animals.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Insects were particularly successful and even today make up the majority of animal species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Amphibians first appeared around 364 million years ago, followed by early amniotes and birds around 155 million years ago (both from "reptile"-like lineages), mammals around 129 million years ago, Homininae around 10 million years ago and modern humans around 250,000 years ago.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] However, despite the evolution of these large animals, smaller organisms similar to the types that evolved early in this process continue to be highly successful and dominate the Earth, with the majority of both biomass and species being prokaryotes.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The proposal that one type of organism could descend from another type goes back to some of the first pre-Socratic Greek philosophers, such as Anaximander and Empedocles.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Such proposals survived into Roman times.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The poet and philosopher Lucretius followed Empedocles in his masterwork *De rerum natura* (lit.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In contrast to these materialistic views, Aristotelianism had considered all natural things as actualisations of fixed natural possibilities, known as forms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] This became part of a medieval teleological understanding of nature in which all things have an intended role to play in a divine cosmic order.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] A number of Arab Muslim scholars wrote about evolution, most notably Ibn Khaldun, who wrote the book *Muqaddimah* in 1377, in which he asserted that humans developed from "the world of the monkeys", in a process by which "species become more numerous".
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The Scientific Revolution ("New Science") of the 17th century rejected the Aristotelian approach.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] It sought to explain natural phenomena in terms of physical laws that were the same for all visible things and that did not require the existence of any fixed natural categories or divine cosmic order.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] However, this new approach was slow to take root in the biological sciences: the last bastion of the concept of fixed natural types.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The biological classification introduced by Carl Linnaeus in 1735 explicitly recognised the hierarchical nature of species relationships, but still viewed species as fixed according to a divine plan.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Other naturalists of this time speculated on the evolutionary change of species over time according to natural laws.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In 1751, Pierre Louis Maupertuis wrote of natural modifications occurring during reproduction and accumulating over many generations to produce new species.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon, suggested that species could degenerate into different organisms, and Erasmus Darwin proposed that all warm-blooded animals could have descended from a single microorganism (or "filament").
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] (The latter process was later called Lamarckism.) These ideas were condemned by established naturalists as speculation lacking empirical support.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In particular, Georges Cuvier insisted that species were unrelated and fixed, their similarities reflecting divine design for functional needs.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In the meantime, Ray's ideas of benevolent design had been developed by William Paley into the *Natural Theology or Evidences of the Existence and Attributes of the Deity* (1802), which proposed complex adaptations as evidence of divine design and which was admired by Charles Darwin.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The crucial break from the concept of constant typological classes or types in biology came with the theory of evolution through natural selection, which was formulated by Charles Darwin and Alfred Wallace in terms of variable populations.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Darwin used the expression *descent with modification* rather than *evolution*.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Partly influenced by *An Essay on the Principle of Population* (1798) by Thomas Robert Malthus, Darwin noted that population growth would lead to a "struggle for existence" in which favourable variations prevailed as others perished.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In each generation, many offspring fail to survive to an age of reproduction because of limited resources.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] This could explain the diversity of plants and animals from a common ancestry through the working of natural laws in the same way for all types of organism.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Darwin developed his theory of "natural selection" from 1838 onwards and was writing up his "big book" on the subject when Alfred Russel Wallace sent him a version of virtually the same theory in 1858.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Their separate papers were presented together at an 1858 meeting of the Linnean Society of London.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] At the end of 1859, Darwin's publication of his "abstract" as *On the Origin of Species* explained natural selection in detail and in a way that led to an increasingly wide acceptance of Darwin's concepts of evolution at the expense of alternative theories.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Thomas Henry Huxley applied Darwin's ideas to humans, using palaeontology and comparative anatomy to provide strong evidence that humans and apes shared a common ancestry.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Some were disturbed by this since it implied that humans did not have a special place in the universe.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Marsh, America's first palaeontologist, was the first to provide solid fossil evidence to support Darwin's theory of evolution by unearthing the ancestors of the modern horse.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In 1877, Marsh delivered a very influential speech before the annual meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of Science, providing a demonstrative argument for evolution.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] For the first time, Marsh traced the evolution of vertebrates from fish all the way through humans.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Sparing no detail, he listed a wealth of fossil examples of past life forms.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The significance of this speech was immediately recognised by the scientific community, and it was printed in its entirety in several scientific journals.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In 1880, Marsh caught the attention of the scientific world with the publication of *Odontornithes: a Monograph on Extinct Birds of North America,* which included his discoveries of birds with teeth.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] These skeletons helped bridge the gap between dinosaurs and birds, and provided invaluable support for Darwin's theory of evolution.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Darwin wrote to Marsh saying, "Your work on these old birds & on the many fossil animals of N.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] America has afforded the best support to the theory of evolution, which has appeared within the last 20 years" (since Darwin's publication of *Origin of Species*).
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The mechanisms of reproductive heritability and the origin of new traits remained a mystery.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Towards this end, Darwin developed his provisional theory of pangenesis.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In 1865, Gregor Mendel reported that traits were inherited in a predictable manner through the independent assortment and segregation of elements (later known as genes).
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Mendel's laws of inheritance eventually supplanted most of Darwin's pangenesis theory.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] August Weismann made the important distinction between germ cells that give rise to gametes (such as sperm and egg cells) and the somatic cells of the body, demonstrating that heredity passes through the germ line only.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Hugo de Vries connected Darwin's pangenesis theory to Weismann's germ/soma cell distinction and proposed that Darwin's pangenes were concentrated in the cell nucleus and when expressed they could move into the cytoplasm to change the cell's structure.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] De Vries was also one of the researchers who made Mendel's work well known, believing that Mendelian traits corresponded to the transfer of heritable variations along the germline.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] To explain how new variants originate, de Vries developed a mutation theory that led to a temporary rift between those who accepted Darwinian evolution and biometricians who allied with de Vries.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In the 1930s, pioneers in the field of population genetics, such as Ronald Fisher, Sewall Wright and J.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Haldane set the foundations of evolution onto a robust statistical philosophy.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The false contradiction between Darwin's theory, genetic mutations, and Mendelian inheritance was thus reconciled.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In the 1920s and 1930s, the modern synthesis connected natural selection and population genetics, based on Mendelian inheritance, into a unified theory that included random genetic drift, mutation, and gene flow.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] This new version of evolutionary theory focused on changes in allele frequencies in population.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] It explained patterns observed across species in populations, through fossil transitions in palaeontology.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Since then, further syntheses have extended evolution's explanatory power in the light of numerous discoveries, to cover biological phenomena across the whole of the biological hierarchy from genes to populations.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The publication of the structure of DNA by James Watson and Francis Crick with contribution of Rosalind Franklin in 1953 demonstrated a physical mechanism for inheritance.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Molecular biology improved understanding of the relationship between genotype and phenotype.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Advances were also made in phylogenetic systematics, mapping the transition of traits into a comparative and testable framework through the publication and use of evolutionary trees.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] One extension, known as evolutionary developmental biology and informally called "evo-devo", emphasises how changes between generations (evolution) act on patterns of change within individual organisms (development).
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Since the beginning of the 21st century, some biologists have argued for an extended evolutionary synthesis, which would account for the effects of non-genetic inheritance modes, such as epigenetics, parental effects, ecological inheritance and cultural inheritance, and evolvability.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In the 19th century, particularly after the publication of *On the Origin of Species* in 1859, the idea that life had evolved was an active source of academic debate centred on the philosophical, social and religious implications of evolution.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Today, the modern evolutionary synthesis is accepted by a vast majority of scientists.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] However, evolution remains a contentious concept for some theists.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] While various religions and denominations have reconciled their beliefs with evolution through concepts such as theistic evolution, there are creationists who believe that evolution is contradicted by the creation myths found in their religions and who raise various objections to evolution.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] In some countries, notably the United States, these tensions between science and religion have fuelled the current creation–evolution controversy, a religious conflict focusing on politics and public education.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] While other scientific fields such as cosmology and Earth science also conflict with literal interpretations of many religious texts, evolutionary biology experiences significantly more opposition from religious literalists.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The teaching of evolution in American secondary school biology classes was uncommon in most of the first half of the 20th century.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The Scopes trial decision of 1925 caused the subject to become very rare in American secondary biology textbooks for a generation, but it was gradually re-introduced later and became legally protected with the 1968 *Epperson v.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] Since then, the competing religious belief of creationism was legally disallowed in secondary school curricula in various decisions in the 1970s and 1980s, but it returned in pseudoscientific form as intelligent design (ID), to be excluded once again in the 2005 *Kitzmiller v.
[src:evolution/evolution-p02] The debate over Darwin's ideas did not generate significant controversy in China.
